`crates/ctx-context` is the crate root: a binary+lib that computes and
delivers the rollup/intent/`.ctx` context chain for a path, either via
direct CLI invocation or a fail-open Claude Code hook mode. Depending on
this crate as a library gets you exactly two entry points —
`cli::dispatch` and `hook::run` — everything else is internal.

The manifest (`Cargo.toml`) fixes the two binary/lib entry points that
must stay in sync with `src/lib.rs`/`src/main.rs`, and pulls in `clap`
(CLI parsing) and `thiserror` (the `CtxError` taxonomy used crate-wide
instead of `anyhow`). `src/` holds the actual pipeline — path validation,
chain assembly, rendering, session-scoped dedup, and the two callers
(hook and CLI) that must agree on `session::ENV_SESSION_ID` and the
"nothing new" `Option<Vec<Node>>` convention. `tests/` exercises that
pipeline end-to-end against an in-memory `FakeEnv`, never real disk I/O,
and is split so that chain/render behavior and hook/session dedup
behavior are pinned in separate files that must be updated together
whenever a change touches code both traverse (e.g. `chain_for` inside
`hook::run`).

The crate-spanning invariant carried from `src/`: hook mode must never
error or panic, only degrade to empty/placeholder output — this is
enforced in `src/` and independently checked in `tests/hook_session.rs`.
Any change to `Env::is_dir`/path lookup semantics in `src/env.rs` must
preserve the prefix-inference convention both test fakes depend on, or
`tests/` breaks wholesale.

No intent.md exists for this directory, so no divergence check applies.